# Introduction

Throughout Chapter 2, we explored the principles, processes, and governance structures that form the foundation of modern risk management.

Rather than viewing risk management as a series of isolated activities, organizations should understand it as a continuous and integrated process that supports strategic objectives, operational resilience, regulatory compliance, and informed decision-making.

This review consolidates the concepts introduced throughout the chapter and demonstrates how they work together to create an effective enterprise risk management program.

In this first part, we will revisit the foundations of risk management, risk governance, and risk identification.

